[tool_use python id=toolu_0154Lv2eAMjpAucvLKuW1Ex4] {"human_description":"Writing phase1a findings markdown note","environment":"rdkit","code":"\nnote = r\"\"\"# Phase 1a Findings — Lac-Phe Analog Pharmacophore Fidelity + Hydrolytic-Stability QM\n\n**Goal:** identify Lac-Phe analogs that (i) preserve the 3D pharmacophore of the parent\nN-lactoyl-L-phenylalanine and (ii) resist hydrolysis of the central scissile linkage.\nTarget-free, CPU-only. 7 molecules: parent amide + 6 analogs.\n\n## Methods (brief)\n- **Conformers:** RDKit ETKDGv3, 50 embeddings, 0.5 Å RMSD pruning, MMFF94 minimization; global-min conformer kept. Per-molecule ensemble SDFs saved.\n- **Fidelity:** RDKit Open3DAlign (O3A, MMFF) of each analog's best conformer onto the parent's; shape Tanimoto (1 − ShapeTanimotoDist); 3D displacement of the three SAR-critical groups (terminal carboxylate C, lactoyl secondary OH, central linkage N) after alignment. Composite `fidelity_score` = 0.4·shapeT + 0.4·(inverse key-group deviation) + 0.2·O3A, min-max normalized across analogs.\n- **QM stability:** GFN2-xTB, geometry optimization with implicit water (`--alpb water`), neutral acid form, full molecules (32–35 atoms; all converged). Scissile-bond Wiberg bond order + Mulliken charges on the linkage atoms.\n\n## Pharmacophore fidelity (ranked)\n| Rank | Analog | shapeT | O3A | mean key-group dev (Å) | Note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | alpha-Me-Phe | 0.58 | 114 | 0.45 | ⚠ **recognition risk** (see below) |\n| 2 | 1,2,3-triazole | 0.60 | 93 | 1.76 | loses amide N-H donor + carbonyl; lactoyl-OH swings ~3.9 Å |\n| 3 | D-Phe | 0.50 | 105 | 0.86 | inverted α-center throws carboxylate ~2.4 Å off-parent |\n| 4 | Thioamide (C=S) | 0.41 | 96 | 0.47 | near-isosteric geometry; C=S weaker acceptor, N-H stronger donor |\n| 5 | N-Me amide | 0.43 | 81 | 1.06 | loses the central amide N-H **donor** (tertiary amide) |\n| 6 | Reduced amide (CH2-NH) | 0.48 | 86 | 4.27 | carbonyl acceptor lost + flexible basic amine; poor overlay |\n\n**⚠ alpha-Me-Phe recognition flag:** its 3D overlay is the best of the set (all three key\ngroups within ~0.45 Å, highest O3A), but this is a geometric artifact. Published SAR on\namino-acid / taste (T1R) receptors shows that methylating the α-hydrogen — creating a\nquaternary α-carbon — sharply reduces receptor affinity because the α-C·H / α-amino\nrecognition motif is blocked. **A good overlay does not rescue this liability; treat\nalpha-Me-Phe as high recognition risk despite its top fidelity score.**\n\n## Hydrolytic stability (GFN2-xTB, ranked most→least inert)\n| Rank | Linkage | scissile C–N Wiberg BO | scissile C charge | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | 1,2,3-triazole | 0.98 | +0.01 | **Genuinely inert** — no carbonyl electrophile; aromatic heterocycle. Best. |\n| 2 | Reduced amide (CH2-NH) | 1.01 | ~0.00 | **Genuinely inert** — carbonyl removed; sp3 C–N single bond is not a hydrolysis substrate. |\n| 3 | Thioamide (C=S) | 1.39 | +0.14 | Modestly more inert — highest C–N double-bond character, least electrophilic scissile C; resists peptidase cleavage but retains hydrolyzable C=S. |\n| 4 | N-Me amide | 1.33 | +0.25 | Marginal — still a hydrolyzable amide; only steric protection. |\n| 5 | Lac-Phe (parent) | 1.32 | +0.26 | Baseline liability — electrophilic amide carbonyl. |\n\n**Important interpretation:** raw scissile-bond order alone is *misleading*. Thioamide has the\nhighest C–N bond order (1.39, strong amide-like resonance) yet still carries a hydrolyzable\nthiocarbonyl. The two backbone replacements that show C–N ≈ 1.0 (triazole, reduced amide) are\nthe genuinely higher-barrier isosteres precisely because they **eliminate the electrophilic\ncarbonyl** — hydrolysis needs a C=O/C=S to attack, and neither has one. So the descriptor is\nread in two regimes: *within the amide-retaining series* (parent/N-Me/thioamide) higher BO +\nlower carbonyl-carbon charge = slower attack (thioamide > N-Me ≈ parent); *the no-carbonyl\nisosteres sit in a different class entirely* and are non-hydrolyzable.\n\n## Combined read — best candidates\n- **1,2,3-triazole** — the only analog that is both a top-2 pharmacophore match (highest shape\n  Tanimoto, 0.60) **and** the most hydrolytically inert. Cost: loses the amide N-H donor and the\n  lactoyl-OH position shifts ~3.9 Å; worth checking whether the OH/donor vectors matter once a\n  receptor hypothesis exists. **Strongest all-round candidate.**\n- **Thioamide** — near-isosteric geometry (key groups within 0.5 Å) with a real, if modest,\n  electronic stabilization and good enzymatic resistance. Conservative pick that changes shape\n  least; stability gain is incremental, not dramatic.\n- **Reduced amide** — fully hydrolysis-inert but the worst pharmacophore match (4.3 Å mean\n  key-group deviation, new basic amine). Stability without recognition — likely too disruptive.\n- **alpha-Me-Phe** — do **not** advance on fidelity score alone; α-methylation is a known\n  recognition-killer (flagged).\n- **N-Me amide / D-Phe** — N-Me gives little stability and loses a donor; D-Phe keeps chemistry\n  but the inverted stereocenter displaces the carboxylate. Lower priority.\n\n**Recommendation for Phase 1b:** prioritize **triazole** (stability + shape) and **thioamide**\n(minimal shape perturbation) for any downstream target-based or MD work; carry reduced-amide as\na stability control; deprioritize alpha-Me-Phe, N-Me, and D-Phe.\n\n*Caveats:* single global-min conformer used for alignment (not full-ensemble O3A); MMFF/GFN2-xTB\nare approximate (no explicit hydrolysis transition state computed — bond order/charge are\nground-state proxies for lability, not activation barriers); neutral acid form modeled (carboxylate\nis anionic at physiological pH); recognition claims are SAR-literature-based, not from a validated\nLac-Phe receptor.\n\"\"\"\nopen(\"phase1a_findings.md\",\"w\").write(note)\nprint(\"wrote\", len(note), \"chars\")\n"}

